# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adipose-tissue
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In humans, DNP causes dose-dependent mitochondrial uncoupling, causing the rapid loss of ATP as heat and leading to uncontrolled hyperthermia—up to 44 °C (111 °F)—and death in case of overdose.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Researchers noticed its effect on raising the basal metabolic rate in accidental exposure and developed it as one of the first weight loss drugs in the early twentieth century.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP was banned from human use by the end of the 1930s due to its risk of death and toxic side effects.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP continues to be used after its ban and experienced a resurgence in popularity after it became available on the Internet.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] It sublimes, is volatile with steam, and is soluble in most organic solvents as well as aqueous alkaline solutions.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP can be produced by hydrolysis of 2,4-dinitrochlorobenzene.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Other routes of DNP synthesis include nitration of monochlorobenzene, nitration of benzene with nitrogen dioxide and mercurous nitrate, oxidation of 1,3-dinitrobenzene, and nitration of phenol with nitric acid.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Nitration of phenol is not practical commercially because partial decomposition of the phenolic ring occurs.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] A dust explosion is possible with DNP in powder or granular form in the presence of air.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP may explosively decompose when submitted to shock, friction or concussion, and may explode upon heating.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP forms explosive salts with strong bases as well as ammonia, and emits toxic fumes of nitrogen dioxide when heated to decomposition.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Historically, DNP has been used as an antiseptic and as a non-selective bioaccumulating pesticide.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP was particularly useful as a herbicide alongside other closely related dinitrophenol herbicides like 2,4-dinitro-*o*-cresol (DNOC), dinoseb and dinoterb.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Since 1998 DNP has been withdrawn from agricultural use.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Currently, there are no actively registered pesticides containing DNP in the United States or Europe.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Dinoseb is used industrially as a polymerisation inhibitor during styrene production.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In 2023, the Home Office said it could not determine any legitimate industrial uses for DNP in the United Kingdom.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] It is a chemical intermediate in the production of sulfur dyes, wood preservatives and picric acid.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] A precursor to 2,4,6-trinitrotoluene (TNT), DNP has also been used to make photographic developers and explosives.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP is classified as an explosive in the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP raises energy expenditure by 30 to 40 percent and causes a weight loss of 0.7–0.9 kilograms (1.5–2.0 lb) per week.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Although DNP is no longer in clinical use as a weight loss drug due to its dangerous side effects, its mechanism of action remains under investigation as a potential approach for treating obesity and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Researchers developed a prodrug, HU6, which is metabolized to DNP in the liver to provide more stable blood concentrations.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] HU6 completed a phase II trial in which it produced significant reductions in liver fat and body weight in overweight people with elevated liver fat, without serious adverse effects.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP is used by bodybuilders, fitness enthusiasts, and people with an eating disorder to lose weight.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The user profile is similar to that of anabolic steroids; many perceive it to be effective and with manageable risks.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Despite health warnings from regulators, DNP is readily available online sometimes under other names such as Dinosan, Dnoc, Solfo Black, Nitrophen, Aldifen, and Chemox.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP is often sold in tablets containing 100 to 200 mg and may be sold alongside other substances such as anabolic steroids and thyroxine.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] It may also be found as a contaminant in other bodybuilding supplements not advertised as containing DNP.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Online message boards provide information on dosage and regimens for DNP use, and describe the risks of taking the compound and provide advice on how to mitigate hyperthermia.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] According to a study published in 2023, the most commonly reported doses were between 150 to 300 mg/d.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Between 2010 and 2020, reports of overdoses were higher in Australasia, Europe and North America than in Asia, Africa, and South or Central America.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] It is easily absorbed through intact skin, and vapors are absorbed through the respiratory tract.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In living cells, DNP acts as a protonophore, an agent that can shuttle protons (hydrogen cations) across biological membranes.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] It dissipates the proton gradient across the mitochondrial membrane, collapsing the proton motive force that the cell uses to produce most of its ATP chemical energy.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Instead of producing ATP, the energy of the proton gradient is lost as heat.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The inefficiency is proportional to the dose of DNP that is taken.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] As the dose increases and energy production is made more inefficient, metabolic rate increases (and more fat is burned) in order to compensate for the inefficiency and to meet energy demands.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP is probably the best known agent for uncoupling oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The phosphorylation of adenosine diphosphate (ADP) by ATP synthase gets disconnected or uncoupled from oxidation.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP raises the basal metabolic rate (BMR) and lowers T4 (thyroid hormone) levels by increasing T4 metabolism and reducing thyroid hormone secretion.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Because it binds to thyroxine-binding globulin, overall thyroid function may not be affected.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP cannot substitute for thyroid hormone in myxedema.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Information about pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of DNP in humans is limited.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Its major metabolites are 2-amino-4-nitrophenol and 4-amino-2-nitrophenol.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In overdoses, symptom onset can be as soon as 3 hours and the average time to death was 14 hours.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP has a low therapeutic index, meaning that the dosage at which toxicity occurs is not much larger than that required to produce a desired effect.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Individual tolerance to DNP's harmful short- and long-term effects varies greatly.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The most common adverse effect reported is a rash, which could be maculopapular, urticarial, angioedema, or an exfoliative dermatitis.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Cataracts can form, causing a permanent loss of vision in days to months of usage, and permanent deafness has also been reported.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Other adverse effects reported include peripheral neuritis, agranulocytosis, and neutropaenia.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Negative effects on the central nervous system, cardiovascular system, and bone marrow can occur.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In animal studies, DNP acted as a teratogen, mutagen, and carcinogen and caused developmental and reproductive harm.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] An unusually yellow coloring of the skin, mucous membranes, sclera, urine, stomach contents, and internal organs is an indication of DNP exposure, but does not occur in every case.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Contact with skin or inhalation can cause DNP poisoning.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Symptoms are typically mild with dermal exposure, but inhalation can lead to systemic effects, the same way as oral exposure.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Overdose is extremely dangerous; cases reported to poison control centers had a 11.9 percent fatality rate between 2010 and 2020.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Although the lowest published fatal ingested dose is 4.3 mg/kg, a typical overdose death occurs at a higher level of exposure, around 20–50 mg/kg.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The first symptoms to appear are nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and perhaps diarrhea.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The typical overdose syndrome seen with DNP and other phenols is a combination of hyperthermia, tachycardia, diaphoresis, and tachypnoea.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Because of the heat produced during uncoupling, DNP overdose will overpower the body's attempt to maintain thermal homeostasis and cause an uncontrolled, fatal rise in body temperature up to as high as 44 °C (111 °F).
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The disruption of metabolism also leads to the accumulation of potassium and phosphate, potentially contributing to toxicity.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP can cause T wave and ST segment abnormalities; heart muscle, kidney, and liver damage have been found on autopsy.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] According to an analysis of United Kingdom and United States overdose cases, tachycardia, hyperpyrexia, acidosis, and agitation or confusion are independent predictors of overdose death.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] There is no antidote to DNP and management strategies are based on expert opinion and case studies.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Treatment for overdose is supportive, and often involves aggressive cooling using methods such as ice baths and intravenous fluids.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Grundlingh et al. recommend administering activated charcoal if the patient presents within an hour of ingestion and using intravenous vasopressors or inotropes to control blood pressure if necessary.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Intravenous methylthioninium chloride can treat methaemoglobinaemia.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Benzodiazepines can help control seizures and dantrolene has been used in an attempt to control hyperthemia.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) has been used on people who died of DNP overdoses but has no known successful outcomes.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] During World War I, munitions workers in France fell ill and some died from DNP exposure.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Tainter learned of DNP's effect in raising the metabolic rate and causing weight loss and pioneered its use as a weight loss drug.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Although he was aware of DNP's narrow therapeutic index, Tainter tried the drugs on obese patients and published successful results in 1933; average weight loss was 20 pounds (9.1 kg) and most recipients did not report adverse effects.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In 1934, Tainter estimated that at least 100,000 people had been treated with DNP in the United States during its first year on the market and there had been three reported fatalities connected to the drug.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Tainter argued that DNP was highly effective in raising the metabolic rate (up to 50 percent) and avoided the negative circulatory effects of desiccated thyroid, another weight loss drug in use at the time.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Other physicians were less optimistic about the adverse effects of DNP, and in 1935 the American Medical Association's Council on Chemistry and Pharmacy declined to list DNP in the *New and Nonofficial Remedies* on the grounds that its benefits did not exceed its risks to health.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Reports of cataracts forming during DNP usage administered by a physician appeared the same year; in 1936 an ophthalmologist based in San Francisco estimated that 2,500 American women had gone blind from DNP use.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Physician opinion turned against the drug, but many people bought direct-to-consumer preparations of DNP—marketed as a cosmetic rather than a drug to evade existing regulations.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP's risks were highlighted in the *Chamber of Horrors*, an exhibit assembled by the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to explain the limitations of existing American drug regulations.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In 1938, the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act increased the FDA's ability to regulate drugs.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP was deemed so toxic as to be banned for human consumption and in 1940 the FDA reported that there was no evidence of continued sale for this purpose.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Nevertheless, it continued to be used for weight loss.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Loomis and Fritz Albert Lipmann discovered DNP's mechanism of action and reported it in a 1948 publication.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Reports of its use increased in the twenty-first century after the drug became available on the Internet.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Although many militaries are replacing traditional 2,4,6-trinitrotoluene (TNT)-based explosives for insensitive munitions, DNP is a degradation byproduct of the IMX-101 insensitive munition used by the United States Army.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] While the Meisenheimer charge transfer reaction is effective at detecting TNT, it is not effective at detecting many other explosives including DNP.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Researchers are studying colorimetric detection and other methods for DNP to find if water or solids such as soils are contaminated with DNP.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] UiO-66-NH2 can be used to bind to and remove DNP from solution.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP is banned for human consumption in many countries.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Because it has some legitimate uses, in many jurisdictions, DNP is legal to sell, but not for human consumption.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] DNP has been banned by the World Anti-Doping Association since 2015.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Petróczi et al. recommend against campaigns informing people of the risks of DNP because it could increase use of the drug.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] However, Sousa et al. argue that publicity campaigns in the United Kingdom in the early and mid-2010s reduced DNP usage.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In 2015, Interpol and the World Anti-Doping Agency released an orange notice warning of the dangers of DNP.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In 1941, the Eastman Kodak Company, a bulk distributor of DNP, was investigated after some of its product was found in illegal diet pills.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] Nicholas Bachynsky, a Texas physician, provided the drug to patients under the name "Mitcal".
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] He was convicted of violating drug laws in 1986, but continued to work with DNP and was additionally convicted of fraud in 2008.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] In 2018, a seller in the United Kingdom was convicted of manslaughter for selling DNP for human consumption.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The conviction was sent to retrial in 2020 by the English Court of Appeal, where the seller was, once again, convicted of gross negligence manslaughter.
[src:adipose-tissue/2-4-dinitrophenol] The UK government reclassified DNP as a regulated poison with effect from October 2023.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] An **abdomen** (also **belly** or **stomach** in vertebrates, or **metasoma** in arthropods) is the front part of the torso between the thorax (chest) and pelvis in humans and in other vertebrates.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The area occupied by the abdomen is called the abdominal cavity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In arthropods, it is the posterior tagma of the body; it follows the thorax or cephalothorax.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In humans, the abdomen stretches from the thorax at the thoracic diaphragm to the pelvis at the pelvic brim.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The pelvic brim stretches from the lumbosacral joint (the intervertebral disc between L5 and S1) to the pubic symphysis and is the edge of the pelvic inlet.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The space above this inlet and under the thoracic diaphragm is termed the abdominal cavity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The boundary of the abdominal cavity is the abdominal wall in the front and the peritoneal surface at the rear.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In vertebrates, the abdomen is a large body cavity enclosed by the abdominal muscles, at the front and to the sides, and by part of the vertebral column at the back.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Lower ribs can also enclose ventral and lateral walls.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdominal cavity is continuous with, and above, the pelvic cavity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] It is attached to the thoracic cavity by the diaphragm.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Structures such as the aorta, inferior vena cava and esophagus pass through the diaphragm.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Both the abdominal and pelvic cavities are lined by a serous membrane known as the parietal peritoneum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] This membrane is continuous with the visceral peritoneum lining the organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdomen in vertebrates contains a number of organs belonging to, for instance, the digestive system, urinary system, and muscular system.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdominal cavity contains most organs of the digestive system, including the stomach, the small intestine, and the colon with its attached appendix.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Other digestive organs are known as the accessory digestive organs and include the liver, its attached gallbladder, and the pancreas, and these communicate with the rest of the system via various ducts.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The spleen, and organs of the urinary system including the kidneys, and adrenal glands also lie within the abdomen, along with many blood vessels including the aorta and inferior vena cava.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The urinary bladder, uterus, fallopian tubes, and ovaries may be seen as either abdominal organs or as pelvic organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Finally, the abdomen contains an extensive membrane called the peritoneum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] A fold of peritoneum may completely cover certain organs, whereas it may cover only one side of organs that usually lie closer to the abdominal wall.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] This is called the retroperitoneum, and the kidneys and ureters are known as *retroperitoneal* organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] There are three layers of muscles in the abdominal wall.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] They are, from the outside to the inside: external oblique, internal oblique, and transverse abdominal.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The first three layers extend between the vertebral column, the lower ribs, the iliac crest and pubis of the hip.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] All of their fibers merge towards the midline and surround the rectus abdominis in a sheath before joining up on the opposite side at the linea alba.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Strength is gained by the criss-crossing of fibers, such that the external oblique runs downward and forward, the internal oblique upward and forward, and the transverse abdominal horizontally forward.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The transverse abdominal muscle is flat and triangular, with its fibers running horizontally.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] It lies between the internal oblique and the underlying transverse fascia.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] It originates from the inguinal ligament, costal cartilages 7–12, the iliac crest and thoracolumbar fascia.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Inserts into the conjoint tendon, xiphoid process, linea alba and the pubic crest.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The rectus abdominis muscles are long and flat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The muscle is crossed by three fibrous bands called the tendinous intersections.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The rectus abdominis is enclosed in a thick sheath, formed as described above, by fibers from each of the three muscles of the lateral abdominal wall.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] They originate at the pubis bone, run up the abdomen on either side of the linea alba, and insert into the cartilages of the fifth, sixth, and seventh ribs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In the region of the groin, the inguinal canal, is a passage through the layers.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] This gap is where the testes can drop through the wall and where the fibrous cord from the uterus in the female runs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] This is also where weakness can form, and cause inguinal hernias.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The pyramidalis muscle is small and triangular.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] It is located in the lower abdomen in front of the rectus abdominis.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] It originates at the pubic bone and is inserted into the linea alba halfway up to the navel.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Functionally, the human abdomen is where most of the digestive tract is placed and so most of the absorption and digestion of food occurs here.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The alimentary tract in the abdomen consists of the lower esophagus, the stomach, the duodenum, the jejunum, ileum, the cecum and the appendix, the ascending, transverse and descending colons, the sigmoid colon and the rectum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Other vital organs inside the abdomen include the liver, the kidneys, the pancreas and the spleen.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdominal wall is split into the posterior (back), lateral (sides), and anterior (front) walls.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdominal muscles have different important functions.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] They assist as muscles of exhalation in the breathing process during forceful exhalation.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Moreover, these muscles serve as protection for the inner organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Furthermore, together with the back muscles they provide postural support and are important in defining the form.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] When the glottis is closed and the thorax and pelvis are fixed, they are integral in the cough, urination, defecation, childbirth, vomit, and singing functions.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] When the pelvis is fixed, they can initiate the movement of the trunk in a forward motion.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] When the thorax is fixed, they can pull up the pelvis and finally, they can bend the vertebral column sideways and assist in the trunk's rotation.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The transverse abdominis muscle is the deepest muscle; therefore, it cannot be touched from the outside.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] It can greatly affect the body's posture.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The internal obliques are also deep and also affect body posture.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Both of them are involved in rotation and lateral flexion of the spine and are used to bend and support the spine from the front.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The external obliques are more superficial and are also involved in rotation and lateral flexion of the spine.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] They also stabilize the spine when upright.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The rectus abdominis muscle is not the most superficial abdominal muscle.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The tendonous sheath extending from the external obliques cover the rectus abdominis.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The rectus abdominis is the muscle that very fit people develop into "six-pack" abs, though there are five vertical sections on each side.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The two bottom sections are just above the pubic bone and usually not visible.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The rectus abdominals' function is to bend one's back forward (flexion).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The main work of the abdominal muscles is to bend the spine forward when contracting concentrically.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Social and cultural perceptions of the outward appearance of the abdomen has varying significance around the world.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Depending on the type of society, excess weight can be perceived as an indicator of wealth and prestige due to excess food, or as a sign of poor health due to lack of exercise.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In many cultures, bare abdomens are distinctly sexualized and perceived similarly to breast cleavage.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Being key elements of spinal support, and contributors to good posture, it is important to properly exercise the abdominal muscles together with the back muscles because when these are weak or overly tight they can suffer painful spasms and injuries.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] When properly exercised, abdominal muscles contribute to improved posture and balance, reduce the likelihood of back pain episodes, reduce the severity of back pain, protect against injury, help avoid some back surgeries, and help with the healing of back problems, or after spine surgery.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] When strengthened, the abdominal muscles provide flexibility as well.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdominal muscles can be worked by strength and fitness exercises, and through practicing disciplines of general body strength such as Pilates, yoga, tai chi, and jogging.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Abdominal obesity is a condition where abdominal fat or visceral fat, has built up excessively between the abdominal organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] This is associated with a higher risk of heart disease, asthma and type 2 diabetes.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Abdominal trauma is an injury to the abdomen and can involve damage to the abdominal organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] There is an associated risk of severe blood loss and infection.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Injury to the lower chest can cause injuries to the spleen and liver.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] A scaphoid abdomen is when the abdomen is sucked inwards.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In a newborn, it may represent a diaphragmatic hernia.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In general, it is indicative of malnutrition.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Many gastrointestinal diseases affect the abdominal organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] These include stomach disease, liver disease, pancreatic disease, gallbladder and bile duct disease; intestinal diseases include enteritis, coeliac disease, diverticulitis, and irritable bowel syndrome.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Different medical procedures can be used to examine the organs of the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] These include endoscopy, colonoscopy, sigmoidoscopy, enteroscopy, oesophagogastroduodenoscopy and virtual colonoscopy.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] There are also a number of medical imaging techniques that can be used.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Surface landmarks are important in the examination of the abdomen.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In the mid-line, a slight furrow extends from the xiphoid process above to the pubic symphysis below, representing the linea alba in the abdominal wall.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] At about its midpoint sits the umbilicus or navel.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The rectus abdominis on each side of the linea alba stands out in muscular people.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The outline of these muscles is interrupted by three or more transverse depressions indicating the tendinous intersections.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] There is usually one about the xiphoid process, one at the navel, and one in between.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] It is the combination of the linea alba and the tendinous intersections which form the abdominal "six-pack" sought after by many people.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The upper lateral limit of the abdomen is the subcostal margin (at or near the *subcostal plane*) formed by the cartilages of the false ribs (8, 9, 10) joining one another.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The lower lateral limit is the anterior crest of the ilium and Poupart's ligament, which runs from the anterior superior spine of the ilium to the spine of the pubis.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] These lower limits are marked by visible grooves.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Just above the pubic spines on either side are the external abdominal rings, which are openings in the muscular wall of the abdomen through which the spermatic cord emerges in the male, and through which an inguinal hernia may rupture.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] One method by which the location of the abdominal contents can be appreciated is to draw three horizontal and two vertical lines.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The two vertical or mid-Poupart lines are drawn from the point midway between the anterior superior spine and the pubic symphysis on each side, vertically upward to the costal margin.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The right subcostal margin corresponds to the lower limit of the liver, while the right nipple is about half an inch above its upper limit.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdomen can be divided into quadrants or regions to describe the location of an organ or structure.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Classically, quadrants are described as the left upper, left lower, right upper, and right lower.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Quadrants are also often used in describing the site of an abdominal pain.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdomen can also be divided into nine regions.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] These terms stem from "hypo" meaning "below" and "epi" means "above", while "chondron" means "cartilage" (in this case, the cartilage of the rib) and "gaster" means stomach.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The "right iliac fossa" (RIF) is a common site of pain and tenderness in patients who have appendicitis.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The fossa is named for the underlying iliac fossa of the hip bone, and thus is somewhat imprecise.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Most of the anatomical structures that will produce pain and tenderness in this region are not in fact in the concavity of the ileum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Abdominal organs can be highly specialized in some mammals.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] For example, the stomach of ruminants, (a suborder of mammals that includes cattle and sheep), is divided into four chambers – rumen, reticulum, omasum and abomasum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In arthropods, the abdomen is built up of a series of upper plates known as tergites and lower plates known as sternites, the whole being held together by a tough yet stretchable membrane.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In insects, the abdomen contains the insect's digestive tract and reproductive organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] It consists of eleven segments in most orders of insects, though the eleventh segment is absent in the adult of most higher orders.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The number of these segments does vary from species to species with the number of segments visible reduced to only seven in the common honey bee.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In the Collembola (springtails), the abdomen has only six segments.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The abdomen is sometimes highly modified.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In Apocrita (bees, ants and wasps), the first segment of the abdomen is fused to the thorax and is called the propodeum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In ants, the second segment forms the narrow petiole.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Some ants have an additional postpetiole segment, and the remaining segments form the bulbous gaster.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] The petiole and gaster (abdominal segments 2 and onward) are collectively called the metasoma.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Unlike other arthropods, insects possess no legs on the abdomen in adult form, though the Protura do have rudimentary leg-like appendages on the first three abdominal segments, and Archaeognatha possess small, articulated "styli" which are sometimes considered to be rudimentary appendages.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] Many larval insects including the Lepidoptera and the Symphyta (sawflies) have fleshy appendages called prolegs on their abdominal segments (as well as their more familiar thoracic legs), which allow them to grip onto the edges of plant leaves as they walk around.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdomen] In arachnids (spiders, scorpions and relatives), the term "abdomen" is used interchangeably with "opisthosoma" ("hind body"), which is the body section posterior to that bearing the legs and head (the prosoma or cephalothorax).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The **abdominal cavity** is a large body cavity in humans and many other animals that contains organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] It is a part of the abdominopelvic cavity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] It is located below the thoracic cavity, and above the pelvic cavity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Its dome-shaped roof is the thoracic diaphragm, a thin sheet of muscle under the lungs, and its floor is the pelvic inlet, opening into the pelvis.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Organs of the abdominal cavity include the stomach, liver, gallbladder, spleen, pancreas, small intestine, kidneys, large intestine, and adrenal glands.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The abdominal cavity is lined with a protective membrane termed the peritoneum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The inside wall is covered by the parietal peritoneum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The kidneys are located behind the peritoneum, in the retroperitoneum, outside the abdominal cavity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The viscera are also covered by visceral peritoneum.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Between the visceral and parietal peritoneum is the peritoneal cavity, which is a potential space.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] It contains a serous fluid called peritoneal fluid that allows motion.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] This motion is apparent of the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The peritoneum, by virtue of its connection to the two (parietal and visceral) portions, gives support to the abdominal organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The peritoneum divides the cavity into numerous compartments.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] One of these the lesser sac is located behind the stomach and joins into the greater sac via the foramen of Winslow.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Some of the organs are attached to the walls of the abdomen via folds of peritoneum and ligaments, such as the liver and others use broad areas of the peritoneum, such as the pancreas.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The peritoneal ligaments are actually dense folds of the peritoneum that are used to connect viscera to viscera or viscera to the walls of the abdomen.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] They are named in such a way as to show what they connect typically.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] For example, the gastrocolic ligament connects the stomach and colon and the splenocolic ligament connects the spleen and the colon, or sometimes by their shape as the round ligament or triangular ligament.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Mesenteries are folds of peritoneum that are attached to the walls of the abdomen and enclose viscera completely.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] They are supplied with plentiful amounts of blood.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The three most important mesenteries are mesentery for the small intestine, the transverse mesocolon, which attaches the back portion of the colon to the abdominal wall, and the sigmoid mesocolon which enfolds the sigmoid colon.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The omentum are specialized folds of peritoneum that enclose nerves, blood vessels, lymph channels, fatty tissue, and connective tissue.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] First, is the greater omentum that hangs off of the transverse colon and greater curvature of the stomach.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The other is the lesser omentum that extends between the stomach and the liver.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] When fluid collects in the abdominal cavity, this condition is called ascites.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] This is usually not noticeable until enough fluid has collected to distend the abdomen.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The collection of fluid will cause pressure on the viscera, veins, and thoracic cavity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Treatment is directed at the cause of the fluid accumulation.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] One method is to decrease the portal vein pressure, especially useful in treating cirrhosis.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Chylous ascites heals best if the lymphatic vessel involved is closed.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Heart failure can cause recurring ascites.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Another disorder is called peritonitis which usually accompanies inflammatory processes elsewhere.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] It can be caused by damage to an organ, or from a contusion to the abdominal wall from the outside or by surgery.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] It may be brought in by the bloodstream or the lymphatic system.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The most common origin is the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Peritonitis can be acute or chronic, generalized or localized, and may have one origin or multiple origins.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] The omenta can help control the spread of infection; however without treatment, the infection will spread throughout the cavity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] An abscess may also form as a secondary reaction to an infection.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-cavity] Antibiotics have become an important tool in fighting abscesses; however, external drainage is usually required also.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Visceral fat, central abdominal fat, and waist circumference show a strong association with type 2 diabetes.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Visceral fat, also known as organ fat or *intra-abdominal fat*, is located inside the peritoneal cavity, packed in between internal organs and torso, as opposed to subcutaneous fat, which is found underneath the skin, and intramuscular fat, which is found interspersed in skeletal muscle.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Visceral fat is composed of several adipose depots including mesenteric, epididymal white adipose tissue (EWAT), and perirenal fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] An excess of adipose visceral fat is known as central obesity, the "pot belly" or "beer belly" effect, in which the abdomen protrudes excessively.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] This body type is also known as "apple shaped", as opposed to "pear shaped" in which fat is deposited on the hips and buttocks.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Researchers first started to focus on abdominal obesity in the 1980s when they realized it had an important connection to cardiovascular disease, diabetes, and dyslipidemia.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Abdominal obesity was more closely related to metabolic dysfunctions connected with cardiovascular disease than was general obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, insightful and powerful imaging techniques were developed that would further help advance the understanding of the health risks associated with body fat accumulation.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Techniques such as computed tomography and magnetic resonance imaging made it possible to categorize mass of adipose tissue located at the abdominal level into intra-abdominal fat and subcutaneous fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Abdominal obesity is linked with higher cardiovascular events among South Asian ethnic populations.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Abdominal obesity is typically associated with a statistically higher risk of heart disease, hypertension, insulin resistance, and type 2 diabetes (see below).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] With an increase in the waist to hip ratio and overall waist circumference the risk of death increases as well.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Metabolic syndrome is associated with abdominal obesity, blood lipid disorders, inflammation, insulin resistance, type 2 diabetes, and an increased risk of developing cardiovascular disease.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] It is now generally believed that intra-abdominal fat is the depot that conveys the biggest health risk.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Recent validation has concluded that total and regional body volume estimates correlate positively and significantly with biomarkers of cardiovascular risk and that BVI calculations correlate significantly with all biomarkers of cardiovascular risk.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] There are numerous theories as to the exact cause and mechanism in type 2 diabetes.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Central obesity is known to predispose individuals for insulin resistance.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Abdominal fat is especially active hormonally, secreting a group of hormones called adipokines that may possibly impair glucose tolerance.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] But adiponectin, an anti-inflammatory adipokine, which is found in lower concentration in obese and diabetic individuals has shown to be beneficial and protective in type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Insulin resistance is a major feature of diabetes mellitus type 2, and central obesity is correlated with both insulin resistance and T2DM itself.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Increased adiposity (obesity) raises serum resistin levels, which in turn directly correlate to insulin resistance.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Studies have also confirmed a direct correlation between resistin levels and T2DM.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] And it is waistline adipose tissue (central obesity) which seems to be the foremost type of fat deposits contributing to rising levels of serum resistin.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Conversely, serum resistin levels have been found to *decline* with decreased adiposity following medical treatment.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Developing asthma due to abdominal obesity is also a main concern.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] As a result of breathing at low lung volume, the muscles are tighter and the airway is narrower.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Obesity causes decreased tidal volumes due to a reduction in chest expansion that is caused both by the weight on the chest itself and the effect of abdominal obesity on flattening the diaphragm.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] It is commonly seen that people who are obese breathe quickly and often, while inhaling small volumes of air.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] People with obesity are also more likely to be hospitalized for asthma.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] A study has stated that 75% of patients treated for asthma in the emergency room were either overweight or obese.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Based on studies, it is evident that obesity has a strong association with vascular and metabolic disease which could potentially be linked to Alzheimer's disease.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Recent studies have also shown an association between mid-life obesity and dementia, but the relationship between later life obesity and dementia is less clear.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] (2010) examining over 700 adults found evidence to suggest higher volumes of visceral fat, regardless of overall weight, were associated with smaller brain volumes and increased risk of dementia.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Alzheimer's disease and abdominal obesity has a strong correlation and with metabolic factors added in, the risk of developing Alzheimer's disease was even higher.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Based on logistic regression analyses, it was found that obesity was associated with an almost 10-fold increase risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Abdominal obesity has been associated with an increased risk of several cancers, particularly malignancies of the digestive system.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These include colorectal, pancreatic, and esophageal cancers.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These associations often remain even after adjustment for overall body mass index, which suggests that abdominal fat distribution is an independent risk factor.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] In women, abdominal obesity has also been linked to higher rates of breast cancer in both the pre- and post-menopausal periods, beyond the effects of general obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Abdominal obesity is an important risk factor for obstructive sleep apnea, as increased abdominal fat can place pressure on the airway and narrow it.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] This can lead to reduced lung volumes during sleep.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Higher waist circumference and waist-to-hip ratio are associated with obstructive sleep apnea, even in individuals whose body mass index is only in the overweight range.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Central obesity can be a feature of lipodystrophies, a group of diseases that is either inherited, or due to secondary causes (often protease inhibitors, a group of medications against AIDS).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Central obesity is a symptom of Cushing's syndrome and is also common in patients with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Central obesity is associated with glucose intolerance and dyslipidemia.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Once dyslipidemia becomes a severe problem, an individual's abdominal cavity would generate elevated free fatty acid flux to the liver.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The effect of abdominal adiposity occurs not just in those who are obese, but also affects people who are non-obese and it also contributes to insulin sensitivity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] (2007) examined whether abdominal circumference is a more reliable indicator than BMI or the presence of knee osteoarthritis in obese patients.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] They found that it actually appears to be a factor linked with the presence of knee pain as well as osteoarthritis in obese study subjects.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] (2007) concluded that a high abdominal circumference is associated with great functional repercussion.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Research published in The Lancet (2023) found that high levels of visceral fat were related to poorer cognitive performance.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The findings suggest that maintaining a healthy weight and metabolic health may be important for preserving cognitive function.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The currently prevalent belief is that the immediate cause of obesity is net energy imbalance—the organism consumes more usable calories than it expends, wastes, or discards through elimination.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Some studies indicate that visceral adiposity, together with lipid dysregulation and decreased insulin sensitivity, is related to the excessive consumption of fructose.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Some evidence shows that in regards to juveniles, when free fructose is present as children's fat cells mature, it makes more of these cells mature into fat cells in the abdominal region.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] It also caused both visceral fat and subcutaneous fat to be less sensitive to insulin.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These effects were not attenuated when compared to similar glucose consumption.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Intake of trans fat from industrial oils has been associated with increased abdominal obesity in men and increased weight and waist circumference in women.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These associations were not attenuated when fat intake and calorie intake was accounted for.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Greater meat (processed meat, red meat, and poultry) consumption has also been positively associated with greater weight gain, and specifically abdominal obesity, even when accounting for calories.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Conversely, studies suggest that oily fish consumption is negatively associated with total body fat and abdominal fat distribution even when body mass remains constant.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Similarly, increased soy protein consumption is correlated with lower amounts of abdominal fat in postmenopausal women even when calorie consumption is controlled.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Numerous large studies have demonstrated that ultra-processed foods have a positive dose-dependent relationship with both abdominal obesity and general obesity in both men and women.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Consuming a diet rich in unprocessed food and minimally processed food is linked with lower obesity risk, lower waist circumference and less chronic disease.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These findings are consistent among American, Canadian, Latin American, Australian, British, French, Spaniard, Swedish, South Korean, Chinese and Sub-Saharan African populations.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Obesity plays an important role in the impairment of lipid and carbohydrate metabolism shown in high-carbohydrate diets.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] It has also been shown that quality protein intake during a 24-hour period and the number of times the essential amino acid threshold of approximately 10 g has been achieved is inversely related to the percentage of central abdominal fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Quality protein uptake is defined as the ratio of essential amino acids to daily dietary protein.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Visceral fat cells will release their metabolic by-products in the portal circulation, where the blood leads straight to the liver.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Thus, the excess of triglycerides and fatty acids created by the visceral fat cells will go into the liver and accumulate there.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] In the liver, most of it will be stored as fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] This concept is known as 'lipotoxicity'.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] A study has shown that alcohol consumption is directly associated with waist circumference and with a higher risk of abdominal obesity in men, but not in women.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Further research is needed to determine whether a significant relationship between alcohol consumption and abdominal obesity exists among women who consume higher amounts of alcohol.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] A systemic review and meta-analysis failed to find data pointing towards a dose-dependent relationship between beer intake and general obesity or abdominal obesity at low or moderate intake levels (under ~500 mL/day).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] However, high beer intake (above ~4 L/wk) appeared to be associated with a higher degree of abdominal obesity specifically, particularly among men.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The prevalence of abdominal obesity is increasing in Western populations, possibly due to a combination of low physical activity and high-calorie diets, and also in developing countries, where it is associated with the urbanization of populations.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Other environmental factors, such as maternal smoking, estrogenic compounds in the diet, and endocrine-disrupting chemicals may be important also.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Hypercortisolism, such as in Cushing's syndrome, also leads to central obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Many prescription drugs, such as dexamethasone and other steroids, can also have side effects resulting in central obesity, especially in the presence of elevated insulin levels.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] In those with a body mass index (BMI) under 35, intra-abdominal body fat is related to negative health outcomes independent of total body fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Intra-abdominal or visceral fat has a particularly strong correlation with cardiovascular disease.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] BMI and waist measurements are well recognized ways to characterize obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] However, waist measurements are not as accurate as BMI measurements.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Waist measurement (*e.g.*, for BFP standard) is more prone to errors than measuring height and weight (*e.g.*, for BMI standard).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] BMI will illustrate the best estimate of one's total body fatness, while waist measurement gives an estimate of visceral fat and risk of obesity-related disease.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] It is recommended to use both methods of measurements.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] While central obesity can be obvious just by looking at the naked body (see the picture), the severity of central obesity is determined by taking waist and hip measurements.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The absolute waist circumference 102 centimetres (40 in) in men and 88 centimetres (35 in) in women and the waist–hip ratio (>0.9 for men and >0.85 for women) are both used as measures of central obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] A differential diagnosis includes distinguishing central obesity from ascites and intestinal bloating.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] In the cohort of 15,000 people participating in the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES III), waist circumference explained obesity-related health risk better than BMI when metabolic syndrome was taken as an outcome measure and this difference was statistically significant.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] In other words, excessive waist circumference appears to be more of a risk factor for metabolic syndrome than BMI.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Another measure of central obesity which has shown superiority to BMI in predicting cardiovascular disease risk is the Index of Central Obesity (waist-to-height ratio, WHtR), where a ratio of >=0.5 (i.e. a waist circumference at least half of the individual's height) is predictive of increased risk.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Another diagnosis of obesity is the analysis of intra-abdominal fat having the most risk to one's personal health.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The increased amount of fat in this region relates to the higher levels of plasma lipid and lipoproteins as per studies mentioned by Eric Poehlman (1998) review.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] An increasing acceptance of the importance of central obesity within the medical profession as an indicator of health risk has led to new developments in obesity diagnosis such as the Body Volume Index, which measures central obesity by measuring a person's body shape and their weight distribution.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Index of Central Obesity (ICO) is the ratio of waist circumference and height first proposed by a Parikh *et al.* in 2007 as a better substitute to the widely used waist circumference in defining metabolic syndrome.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The National Cholesterol Education Program Adult Treatment Panel III suggested cutoff of 102 cm (40 in) and 88 cm (35 in) for males and females as a marker of central obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The same was used in defining metabolic syndrome.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Misra et al. suggested that these cutoffs are not applicable among Indians and the cutoffs be lowered to 90 cm (35 in) and 80 cm (31 in) for males and females.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Various race specific cutoffs were suggested by different groups.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The International Diabetes Federation defined central obesity based on these various race and gender specific cutoffs.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The other limitation of waist circumference is that it the measurement procedure has not been standardized and in children there are no, or few, comparison standards or reference data.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Parikh et al. looked at the average heights of various races and suggested that by using ICO various race- and gender-specific cutoffs of waist circumference can be discarded.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] An ICO cutoff of 0.53 was suggested as a criterion to define central obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Parikh *et al.* further tested a modified definition of metabolic syndrome in which waist circumference was replaced with ICO in the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) database and found the modified definition to be more specific and sensitive.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] This parameter has been used in the study of metabolic syndrome and cardiovascular disease.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Central obesity in individuals with normal BMI is referred to as normal weight obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] There are sex-dependent differences in regional fat distribution.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Males are more susceptible to upper-body fat accumulation, most likely in the belly, due to sex hormone differences.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] When comparing the body fat of men and women it is seen that men have close to twice the visceral fat as that of pre-menopausal women.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] In women, estrogen is believed to cause fat to be stored in the buttocks, thighs, and hips.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] When women reach menopause and the estrogen produced by ovaries declines, fat at their buttocks, hips, and thighs decreases while fat at their belly increases.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] 50% of men and 70% of women in the United States between the ages of 50 and 79 years now exceed the waist circumference threshold for central obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Central obesity is positively associated with coronary heart disease risk in women and men.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] It has been hypothesized that the sex differences in fat distribution may explain the sex difference in coronary heart disease risk.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Even with the differences, at any given level of central obesity measured as waist circumference or waist to hip ratio, coronary artery disease rates are identical in men and women.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] A permanent routine of exercise, eating healthily, and, during periods of being overweight, consuming the same number or fewer calories than used will prevent and help fight obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] A single pound of fat yields approximately 3500 calories of energy (32 000 kJ energy per kilogram of fat), and weight loss is achieved by reducing energy intake, or increasing energy expenditure, thus achieving a negative balance.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Adjunctive therapies which may be prescribed by a physician are orlistat or sibutramine, although the latter has been associated with increased cardiovascular events and strokes and has been withdrawn from the market in the US, the UK, the EU, Australia, Canada, Hong Kong, and Thailand.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] A 2006 study published in the *International Journal of Sport Nutrition and Exercise Metabolism* suggests that combining cardiovascular (aerobic) exercise with resistance training is more effective than cardiovascular training alone in getting rid of abdominal fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] An additional benefit to exercising is that it reduces stress and insulin levels, which reduce the presence of cortisol, a hormone that leads to more belly fat deposits and leptin resistance.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] In the presence of type 2 diabetes, the physician might instead prescribe metformin and thiazolidinediones (rosiglitazone or pioglitazone) as antidiabetic drugs rather than sulfonylurea derivatives.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Thiazolidinediones may cause slight weight gain but decrease "pathologic" abdominal fat (visceral fat), and therefore may be prescribed for diabetics with central obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Thiazolidinedione has been associated with heart failure and increased cardiovascular risk; so it has been withdrawn from the market in Europe by EMA as of 2010.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] New clinical guidelines support the use of glucagon-like-peptide-1 receptor agonists, such as semaglutide, for adults with abdominal obesity who have not been able to achieve adequate weight reduction with lifestyle modifications.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These medications have largely replaced the use of other anti-diabetic drugs for weight loss.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] GLP-1 agonists have shown clinically meaningful reductions in body weight and abdominal obesity, and demonstrated improvements in cardiovascular health in randomized trials.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] For patients unresponsive to lifestyle and medication management of abdominal obesity, metabolic and bariatric surgical options exist.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These include sleeve gastrectomy and Roux-en-Y gastric bypass surgery.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These surgical options are effective in patients with severe abdominal obesity without significant comorbidities.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Surgery leads to substantial reductions in abdominal obesity, waist circumference, and is associated with improvements in type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and other complications associated with abdominal obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The conclusion was that mean weight decreased significantly in the intervention group from baseline to year 1 by 2.2 kg (*p*<.001) and was 2.2 kg less than the control group change from baseline at year 1.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] This difference from baseline between control and intervention groups diminished over time, but a significant difference in weight was maintained through year 9, the end of the study.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] There is a common misconception that spot exercise (that is, exercising a specific muscle or location of the body) most effectively burns fat at the desired location, but this is not the case.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Spot exercise is beneficial for building specific muscles, but it has little effect, if any, on fat in that area of the body, or on the body's distribution of body fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] The same logic applies to sit-ups and belly fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Sit-ups, crunches and other abdominal exercises are useful in building the abdominal muscles, but they have little effect, if any, on the adipose tissue located there.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] A large central adiposity deposit has been assigned many common use names, including "spare tire", "love handle", "paunch", "boiler", and "potbelly".
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Several colloquial terms used to refer to central obesity, and to people who have it, refer to beer drinking.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] However, there is little scientific evidence that beer drinkers are more prone to central obesity, despite its being known colloquially as "beer belly", "beer gut", or "beer pot".
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] One of the few studies conducted on the subject did not find that beer drinkers are more prone to central obesity than nondrinkers or drinkers of wine or spirits.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Chronic alcoholism can lead to cirrhosis, symptoms of which include gynecomastia (enlarged breasts) and ascites (abdominal fluid).
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] These symptoms can suggest the appearance of central obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Researchers in Copenhagen examined the relationship between waist circumferences and costs among 31,840 subjects aged 50–64 years of age with different waist circumferences.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] Their study showed that an increase in just an additional centimetre above normal waistline caused a 1.25% and 2.08% rise in health care costs in women and men respectively.
[src:adipose-tissue/abdominal-obesity] To put this in perspective, a woman with a waistline of 95 cm (approx 37.4 in) and without underlying health problems or co-morbidities can incur economic costs that are 22%, or US$397, higher per year than a woman with a normal waist circumference.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP can be interconverted to adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ATP contains one more phosphate group than ADP, while AMP contains one fewer phosphate group.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Energy transfer used by all living things is a result of dephosphorylation of ATP by enzymes known as ATPases.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The cleavage of a phosphate group from ATP results in the coupling of energy to metabolic reactions and a by-product of ADP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ATP is continually reformed from lower-energy species ADP and AMP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The biosynthesis of ATP is achieved throughout processes such as substrate-level phosphorylation, oxidative phosphorylation, and photophosphorylation, all of which facilitate the addition of a phosphate group to ADP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP cycling supplies the energy needed to do work in a biological system, the thermodynamic process of transferring energy from one source to another.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] There are two types of energy: potential energy and kinetic energy.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Potential energy can be thought of as stored energy, or usable energy that is available to do work.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Kinetic energy is the energy of an object as a result of its motion.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The significance of ATP is in its ability to store potential energy within the phosphate bonds.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy stored between these bonds can then be transferred to do work.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] For example, the transfer of energy from ATP to the protein myosin causes a conformational change when connecting to actin during muscle contraction.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] It takes multiple reactions between myosin and actin to effectively produce one muscle contraction, and, therefore, the availability of large amounts of ATP is required to produce each muscle contraction.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] For this reason, biological processes have evolved to produce efficient ways to replenish the potential energy of ATP from ADP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Breaking one of ATP's phosphorus bonds generates approximately 30.5 kilojoules per mole of ATP (7.3 kcal).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP can be converted, or powered back to ATP through the process of releasing the chemical energy available in food; in humans, this is constantly performed via aerobic respiration in the mitochondria.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Plants use photosynthetic pathways to convert and store energy from sunlight, also conversion of ADP to ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Animals use the energy released in the breakdown of glucose and other molecules to convert ADP to ATP, which can then be used to fuel necessary growth and cell maintenance.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The ten-step catabolic pathway of glycolysis is the initial phase of free-energy release in the breakdown of glucose and can be split into two phases, the preparatory phase and payoff phase.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP and phosphate are needed as precursors to synthesize ATP in the payoff reactions of the TCA cycle and oxidative phosphorylation mechanism.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] During the payoff phase of glycolysis, the enzymes phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase facilitate the addition of a phosphate group to ADP by way of substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Glycolysis is performed by all living organisms and consists of 10 steps.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 require the input of energy derived from the hydrolysis of ATP to ADP and Pi (inorganic phosphate), whereas steps 7 and 10 require the input of ADP, each yielding ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The enzymes necessary to break down glucose are found in the cytoplasm, the viscous fluid that fills living cells, where the glycolytic reactions take place.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The citric acid cycle, also known as the Krebs cycle or the TCA (tricarboxylic acid) cycle is an 8-step process that takes the pyruvate generated by glycolysis and generates 4 NADH, FADH2, and GTP, which is further converted to ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] It is only in step 5, where GTP is generated, by succinyl-CoA synthetase, and then converted to ATP, that ADP is used (GTP + ADP → GDP + ATP).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Oxidative phosphorylation produces 26 of the 30 equivalents of ATP generated in cellular respiration by transferring electrons from NADH or FADH2 to O2 through electron carriers.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy released when electrons are passed from higher-energy NADH or FADH2 to the lower-energy O2 is required to phosphorylate ADP and once again generate ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] It is this energy coupling and phosphorylation of ADP to ATP that gives the electron transport chain the name oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] During the initial phases of glycolysis and the TCA cycle, cofactors such as NAD+ donate and accept electrons that aid in the electron transport chain's ability to produce a proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The ATP synthase complex exists within the mitochondrial membrane (FO portion) and protrudes into the matrix (F1 portion).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy derived as a result of the chemical gradient is then used to synthesize ATP by coupling the reaction of inorganic phosphate to ADP in the active site of the ATP synthase enzyme; the equation for this can be written as ADP + Pi → ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] Under normal conditions, small disk-shape platelets circulate in the blood freely and without interaction with one another.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP is stored in dense bodies inside blood platelets and is released upon platelet activation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP interacts with a family of ADP receptors found on platelets (P2Y1, P2Y12, and P2X1), which leads to platelet activation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP in the blood is converted to adenosine by the action of ecto-ADPases, inhibiting further platelet activation via adenosine receptors.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:adipose-tissue/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] There are two types of adipose tissue, white adipose tissue (WAT) and brown adipose tissue (BAT), which are also known as white and brown fat, respectively, and comprise two types of fat cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] White fat cells contain a single large lipid droplet surrounded by a layer of cytoplasm, and are known as unilocular.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] The nucleus is flattened and pushed to the periphery.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] A typical fat cell is 0.1 mm in diameter with some being twice that size, and others half that size.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] However, these numerical estimates of fat cell size depend largely on the measurement method and the location of the adipose tissue.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] The fat stored is in a semi-liquid state, and is composed primarily of triglycerides, and cholesteryl ester.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] White fat cells secrete many proteins acting as adipokines such as resistin, adiponectin, leptin and apelin.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] An average human adult has 30 billion fat cells with a weight of 30 lbs or 13.5 kg.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] If a child or adolescent gains sufficient excess weight, fat cells may increase in absolute number until age twenty-four.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] A large meta-analysis has shown that white adipose tissue cell size is dependent on measurement methods, adipose tissue depots, age, and body mass index; for the same degree of obesity, increases in fat cell size were also associated with the dysregulations in glucose and lipid metabolism.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Brown fat cells are polyhedral in shape.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Brown fat is derived from dermatomyocyte cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Unlike white fat cells, these cells have considerable cytoplasm, with several lipid droplets scattered throughout, and are known as multilocular cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] The nucleus is round and, although eccentrically located, it is not in the periphery of the cell.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] The brown color comes from the large quantity of mitochondria.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Brown fat, also known as "baby fat," is used to generate heat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Marrow adipocytes are unilocular like white fat cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] The marrow adipose tissue depot is poorly understood in terms of its physiologic function and relevance to bone health.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Marrow adipose tissue expands in states of low bone density but additionally expands in the setting of obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Marrow adipose tissue response to exercise approximates that of white adipose tissue.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Exercise reduces both adipocyte size as well as marrow adipose tissue volume, as quantified by MRI or μCT imaging of bone stained with the lipid binder osmium.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Mesenchymal stem cells can differentiate into adipocytes, connective tissue, muscle or bone.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] The precursor of the adult cell is termed a lipoblast, and a tumor of this cell type is known as a lipoblastoma.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Fat cells in some mice have been shown to drop in count due to fasting and other properties were observed when exposed to cold.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] If the adipocytes in the body reach their maximum capacity of fat, they may replicate to allow additional fat storage.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] According to some reports and textbooks, the number of adipocytes can increase in childhood and adolescence, though the amount is usually constant in adults.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Individuals who become obese as adults, rather than as adolescents, have no more adipocytes than they had before.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Body fat cells have regional responses to the overfeeding that was studied in adult subjects.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] In the upper body, an increase of adipocyte size correlated with upper-body fat gain; however, the number of fat cells was not significantly changed.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] In contrast to the upper body fat cell response, the number of lower-body adipocytes did significantly increase during the course of experiment.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Notably, there was no change in the size of the lower-body adipocytes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Approximately 10% of fat cells are renewed annually at all adult ages and levels of body mass index without a significant increase in the overall number of adipocytes in adulthood.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Obesity is characterized by the expansion of fat mass, through adipocyte size increase (hypertrophy) and, to a lesser extent, cell proliferation (hyperplasia).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] In the fatty tissue of obese individuals, there is increased production of metabolism modulators, such as glycerol, hormones, macrophage-stimulating chemokines, and pro-inflammatory cytokines, leading to the development of insulin resistance.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Production of these modulators and the resulting pathogenesis of insulin resistance are probably caused by adipocytes as well as immune system macrophages that infiltrate the tissue.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Fat production in adipocytes is strongly stimulated by insulin.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] By controlling the activity of the pyruvate dehydrogenase and the acetyl-CoA carboxylase enzymes, insulin promotes unsaturated fatty acid synthesis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] It also promotes glucose uptake and induces SREBF1, which activates the transcription of genes that stimulate lipogenesis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] SREBF1 (sterol regulatory element-binding transcription factor 1) is a transcription factor synthesized as an inactive precursor protein inserted into the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) membrane by two membrane-spanning helices.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Also anchored in the ER membrane is SCAP (SREBF-cleavage activating protein), which binds SREBF1.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] The SREBF1-SCAP complex is retained in the ER membrane by INSIG1 (insulin-induced gene 1 protein).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] When sterol levels are depleted, INSIG1 releases SCAP and the SREBF1-SCAP complex can be sorted into transport vesicles coated by the coatomer COPII that are exported to the Golgi apparatus.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] In the Golgi apparatus, SREBF1 is cleaved and released as a transcriptionally active mature protein.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] It is then free to translocate to the nucleus and activate the expression of its target genes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Clinical studies have repeatedly shown that even though insulin resistance is usually associated with obesity, the membrane phospholipids of the adipocytes of obese patients generally still show an increased degree of fatty acid unsaturation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] This seems to point to an adaptive mechanism that allows the adipocyte to maintain its functionality, despite the increased storage demands associated with obesity and insulin resistance.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] A study conducted in 2013 found that, while INSIG1 and SREBF1 mRNA expression was decreased in the adipose tissue of obese mice and humans, the amount of active SREBF1 was increased in comparison with normal mice and non-obese patients.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] This downregulation of INSIG1 expression combined with the increase of mature SREBF1 was also correlated with the maintenance of SREBF1-target gene expression.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Hence, it appears that, by downregulating INSIG1, there is a resetting of the INSIG1/SREBF1 loop, allowing for the maintenance of active SREBF1 levels.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] This seems to help compensate for the anti-lipogenic effects of insulin resistance and thus preserve adipocyte fat storage abilities and availability of appropriate levels of fatty acid unsaturation in face of the nutritional pressures of obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Adipocytes can synthesize estrogens from androgens, potentially being the reason why being underweight or overweight are risk factors for infertility.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Additionally, adipocytes are responsible for the production of the hormone leptin.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipocyte] Leptin is important in regulation of appetite and acts as a satiety factor.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Previously treated as being hormonally inert, in recent years adipose tissue has been recognized as a major endocrine organ, as it produces hormones such as leptin, estrogen, resistin, and cytokines (especially TNFα).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In obesity, adipose tissue is implicated in the chronic release of pro-inflammatory markers known as adipokines, which are responsible for the development of metabolic syndrome—a constellation of diseases including type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease and atherosclerosis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is derived from preadipocytes and its formation appears to be controlled in part by the adipose gene.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The two types of adipose tissue are white adipose tissue (WAT), which stores energy, and brown adipose tissue (BAT), which generates body heat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue—more specifically brown adipose tissue—was first identified by the Swiss naturalist Conrad Gessner in 1551.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In humans, adipose tissue is located beneath the skin (subcutaneous fat), around internal organs (visceral fat), in bone marrow (yellow bone marrow), intermuscular (muscular system), and in the breast (breast tissue).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is found in specific locations, which are referred to as *adipose depots*.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In addition to adipocytes, which comprise the highest percentage of cells within adipose tissue, other cell types are present, collectively termed stromal vascular fraction (SVF) of cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] SVF includes preadipocytes, fibroblasts, adipose tissue macrophages, and endothelial cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue contains many small blood vessels.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In the integumentary system, which includes the skin, it accumulates in the deepest level, the subcutaneous layer, providing insulation from heat and cold.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Around organs, it provides protective padding.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Adipose depots in different parts of the body have different biochemical profiles.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Under normal conditions, it provides feedback for hunger and diet to the brain.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In an obese person, excess adipose tissue hanging downward from the abdomen is referred to as a panniculus.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] A panniculus complicates surgery of the morbidly obese individual.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] It may remain as a literal "apron of skin" if a severely obese person loses large amounts of fat (a common result of gastric bypass surgery).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Obesity is treated through exercises, diet, behavioral therapy, and liposuctions.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Reconstructive surgery is one aspect of treatment.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat or abdominal fat (also known as organ fat or intra-abdominal fat) is located inside the abdominal cavity, packed between the organs (stomach, liver, intestines, kidneys, etc.).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is different from subcutaneous fat underneath the skin, and intramuscular fat interspersed in skeletal muscles.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Fat in the lower body, as in thighs and buttocks, is subcutaneous and is not consistently spaced tissue, whereas fat in the abdomen is mostly visceral and semi-fluid.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is composed of several adipose depots, including mesenteric, epididymal white adipose tissue (EWAT), and perirenal depots.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is often expressed in terms of its area in cm2 (VFA, visceral fat area).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] An excess of visceral fat is known as abdominal obesity, or "belly fat", in which the abdomen protrudes excessively.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] New developments such as the Body Volume Index (BVI) are specifically designed to measure abdominal volume and abdominal fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Excess visceral fat is also linked to type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance, inflammatory diseases, and other obesity-related diseases.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Likewise, the accumulation of neck fat (or cervical adipose tissue) has been shown to be associated with mortality.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Several studies have suggested that visceral fat can be predicted from simple anthropometric measures, and predicts mortality more accurately than body mass index or waist circumference.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Men are more likely to have fat stored in the abdomen due to sex hormone differences.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Estrogen (female sex hormone) causes fat to be stored in the buttocks, thighs, and hips in women.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] When women reach menopause and the estrogen produced by the ovaries declines, fat migrates from the buttocks, hips and thighs to the waist; later fat is stored in the abdomen.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat can be caused by excess cortisol levels.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] At least 10 MET-hours per week of aerobic exercise leads to visceral fat reduction in those without metabolic-related disorders.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Resistance training and caloric restriction also reduce visceral fat, although their effect may not be cumulative.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Both exercise and hypocaloric diet cause loss of visceral fat, but exercise has a larger effect on visceral fat versus total fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] High-intensity exercise is one way to effectively reduce total abdominal fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] An energy-restricted diet combined with exercise will reduce total body fat and the ratio of visceral adipose tissue to subcutaneous adipose tissue, suggesting a preferential mobilization for visceral fat over subcutaneous fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Epicardial adipose tissue (EAT) is a particular form of visceral fat deposited around the heart and found to be a metabolically active organ that generates various bioactive molecules, which might significantly affect cardiac function.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Marked component differences have been observed in comparing EAT with subcutaneous fat, suggesting a location-specific impact of stored fatty acids on adipocyte function and metabolism.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Most of the remaining nonvisceral fat is found just below the skin in a region called the hypodermis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] This subcutaneous fat is not related to many of the classic obesity-related pathologies, such as heart disease, cancer, and stroke, and some evidence even suggests it might be protective.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The typically female (or gynecoid) pattern of body fat distribution around the hips, thighs, and buttocks is subcutaneous fat, and therefore poses less of a health risk compared to visceral fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Like all other fat organs, subcutaneous fat is an active part of the endocrine system, secreting the hormones leptin and resistin.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The relationship between the subcutaneous adipose layer and total body fat in a person is often modelled by using regression equations.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The most popular of these equations was formed by Durnin and Wormersley, who rigorously tested many types of skinfold, and, as a result, created two formulae to calculate the body density of both men and women.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] These equations present an inverse correlation between skinfolds and body density—as the sum of skinfolds increases, the body density decreases.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Factors such as sex, age, population size or other variables may make the equations invalid and unusable, and, as of 2012, Durnin and Wormersley's equations remain only estimates of a person's true level of fatness.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Marrow fat, also known as marrow adipose tissue (MAT), is a poorly understood adipose depot that resides in the bone and is interspersed with hematopoietic cells as well as bony elements.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The adipocytes in this depot are derived from mesenchymal stem cells (MSC) which can give rise to fat cells, bone cells as well as other cell types.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The fact that MAT increases in the setting of calorie restriction/ anorexia is a feature that distinguishes this depot from other fat depots.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Exercise regulates MAT, decreasing MAT quantity and diminishing the size of marrow adipocytes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The exercise regulation of marrow fat suggests that it bears some physiologic similarity to other white adipose depots.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Moreover, increased MAT in obesity further suggests a similarity to white fat depots.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Ectopic fat is the storage of triglycerides in tissues other than adipose tissue, that are supposed to contain only small amounts of fat, such as the liver, skeletal muscle, heart, and pancreas.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] This can interfere with cellular functions and hence organ function and is associated with insulin resistance in type-2 diabetes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] It is stored in relatively high amounts around the organs of the abdominal cavity, but is not to be confused with visceral fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The specific cause for the accumulation of ectopic fat is unknown.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The cause is likely a combination of genetic, environmental, and behavioral factors that are involved in excess energy intake and decreased physical activity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Substantial weight loss can reduce ectopic fat stores in all organs and this is associated with an improvement of the function of those organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In the latter case, non-invasive weight loss interventions like diet or exercise can decrease ectopic fat (particularly in heart and liver) in overweight or obese children and adults.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Free fatty acids (FFAs) are liberated from lipoproteins by lipoprotein lipase (LPL) and enter the adipocyte, where they are reassembled into triglycerides by esterifying them onto glycerol.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Human fat tissue contains from 61% to 94% lipids.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Lean and obese individuals tend towards the low and high ends of this range, respectively.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] There is a constant flux of FFAs entering and leaving adipose tissue.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The net direction of this flux is controlled by insulin and leptin—if insulin is elevated, then there is a net inward flux of FFA, and only when insulin is low can FFA leave adipose tissue.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Insulin secretion is stimulated by high blood sugar, which results from consuming carbohydrates.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In humans, lipolysis (hydrolysis of triglycerides into free fatty acids) is controlled through the balanced control of lipolytic B-adrenergic receptors and a2A-adrenergic receptor-mediated antilipolysis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Fat cells have an important physiological role in maintaining triglyceride and free fatty acid levels, as well as determining insulin resistance.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Abdominal fat has a different metabolic profile—being more prone to induce insulin resistance.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] This explains to a large degree why central obesity is a marker of impaired glucose tolerance and is an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease (even in the absence of diabetes mellitus and hypertension).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Recent advances in biotechnology have allowed for the harvesting of adult stem cells from adipose tissue, allowing stimulation of tissue regrowth using a patient's own cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In addition, adipose-derived stem cells from both human and animals reportedly can be efficiently reprogrammed into induced pluripotent stem cells without the need for feeder cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The use of a patient's own cells reduces the chance of tissue rejection and avoids ethical issues associated with the use of human embryonic stem cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] A growing body of evidence also suggests that different fat depots (i.e. abdominal, omental, pericardial) yield adipose-derived stem cells with different characteristics.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] These depot-dependent features include proliferation rate, immunophenotype, differentiation potential, gene expression, as well as sensitivity to hypoxic culture conditions.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Oxygen levels seem to play an important role on the metabolism and in general the function of adipose-derived stem cells.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is a major peripheral source of aromatase in both males and females, contributing to the production of estradiol.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissues also secrete a type of cytokines (cell-to-cell signalling proteins) called adipokines (adipose cytokines), which play a role in obesity-associated complications.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Perivascular adipose tissue releases adipokines such as adiponectin that affect the contractile function of the vessels that they surround.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Brown fat or brown adipose tissue (BAT) is a specialized form of adipose tissue important for adaptive thermogenesis in humans and other mammals.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] BAT can generate heat by "uncoupling" the respiratory chain of oxidative phosphorylation within mitochondria through tissue-specific expression of uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] BAT is primarily located around the neck and large blood vessels of the thorax, where it may effectively act in heat exchange.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] BAT is robustly activated upon cold exposure by the release of catecholamines from sympathetic nerves that results in UCP1 activation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Nearly half of the nerves present in adipose tissue are sensory neurons connected to the dorsal root ganglia.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] BAT activation may also occur in response to overfeeding.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] UCP1 activity is stimulated by long chain fatty acids that are produced subsequent to β-adrenergic receptor activation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] UCP1 is proposed to function as a fatty acid proton symporter, although the exact mechanism has yet to be elucidated.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In contrast, UCP1 is inhibited by ATP, ADP, and GTP.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Attempts to simulate this process pharmacologically have so far been unsuccessful.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Techniques to manipulate the differentiation of "brown fat" could become a mechanism for weight loss therapy in the future, encouraging the growth of tissue with this specialized metabolism without inducing it in other organs.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] A review on the eventual therapeutic targeting of brown fat to treat human obesity was published by Samuelson and Vidal-Puig in 2020.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Until recently, brown adipose tissue in humans was thought to be primarily limited to infants, but new evidence has overturned that belief.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Metabolically active tissue with temperature responses similar to brown adipose was first reported in the neck and trunk of some human adults in 2007, and the presence of brown adipose in human adults was later verified histologically in the same anatomical regions.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Browning of WAT, also referred to as "beiging", occurs when adipocytes within WAT depots develop features of BAT.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] **Beige adipocytes** take on a multilocular appearance (containing several lipid droplets) and increase expression of uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In doing so, these normally energy-storing adipocytes become energy-releasing adipocytes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The calorie-burning capacity of brown and beige fat has been extensively studied as research efforts focus on therapies targeted to treat obesity and diabetes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The drug 2,4-dinitrophenol, which also acts as a chemical uncoupler similarly to UCP1, was used for weight loss in the 1930s.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] However, it was quickly discontinued when excessive dosing led to adverse side effects including hyperthermia and death. β3-adrenergic agonists, like CL316,243, have also been developed and tested in humans.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] However, the use of such drugs has proven largely unsuccessful due to several challenges, including varying species receptor specificity and poor oral bioavailability.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Cold is a primary regulator of BAT processes and induces WAT browning.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Browning in response to chronic cold exposure has been well documented and is a reversible process.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] A study in mice demonstrated that cold-induced browning can be completely reversed in 21 days, with measurable decreases in UCP1 seen within a 24-hour period.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] A study by Rosenwald et al. revealed that when the animals are re-exposed to a cold environment, the same adipocytes will adopt a beige phenotype, suggesting that beige adipocytes are retained.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Transcriptional regulators, as well as a growing number of other factors, regulate the induction of beige fat.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Four regulators of transcription are central to WAT browning and serve as targets for many of the molecules known to influence this process.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] These include peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARγ), PRDM16, peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma coactivator 1 alpha (PGC-1α), and Early B-Cell Factor-2 (EBF2).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The list of molecules that influence browning has grown in direct proportion to the popularity of this topic and is constantly evolving as more knowledge is acquired.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Among these molecules are irisin and fibroblast growth factor 21 (FGF21), which have been well-studied and are believed to be important regulators of browning.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Irisin is secreted from muscle in response to exercise and has been shown to increase browning by acting on beige preadipocytes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] FGF21, a hormone secreted mainly by the liver, has garnered a great deal of interest after being identified as a potent stimulator of glucose uptake and a browning regulator through its effects on PGC-1α.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] It is increased in BAT during cold exposure and is thought to aid in resistance to diet-induced obesity FGF21 may also be secreted in response to exercise and a low protein diet, although the latter has not been thoroughly investigated.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Data from these studies suggest that environmental factors like diet and exercise may be important mediators of browning.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In mice, it was found that beiging can occur through the production of methionine-enkephalin peptides by type 2 innate lymphoid cells in response to interleukin 33.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Due to the complex nature of adipose tissue and a growing list of browning regulatory molecules, great potential exists for the use of bioinformatics tools to improve study within this field.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Studies of WAT browning have greatly benefited from advances in these techniques, as beige fat is rapidly gaining popularity as a therapeutic target for the treatment of obesity and diabetes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] DNA microarray is a bioinformatics tool used to quantify expression levels of various genes simultaneously, and has been used extensively in the study of adipose tissue.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] One such study used microarray analysis in conjunction with Ingenuity IPA software to look at changes in WAT and BAT gene expression when mice were exposed to temperatures of 28 and 6 °C.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The most significantly up- and downregulated genes were then identified and used for analysis of differentially expressed pathways.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] It was discovered that many of the pathways upregulated in WAT after cold exposure are also highly expressed in BAT, such as oxidative phosphorylation, fatty acid metabolism, and pyruvate metabolism.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] This suggests that some of the adipocytes switched to a beige phenotype at 6 °C.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Mössenböck et al. also used microarray analysis to demonstrate that insulin deficiency inhibits the differentiation of beige adipocytes but does not disturb their capacity for browning.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] These two studies demonstrate the potential for the use of microarray in the study of WAT browning.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] RNA sequencing (RNA-Seq) is a powerful computational tool that allows for the quantification of RNA expression for all genes within a sample.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Incorporating RNA-Seq into browning studies is of great value, as it offers better specificity, sensitivity, and a more comprehensive overview of gene expression than other methods.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] RNA-Seq has been used in both human and mouse studies in an attempt characterize beige adipocytes according to their gene expression profiles and to identify potential therapeutic molecules that may induce the beige phenotype.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] One such study used RNA-Seq to compare gene expression profiles of WAT from wild-type (WT) mice and those overexpressing Early B-Cell Factor-2 (EBF2).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] WAT from the transgenic animals exhibited a brown fat gene program and had decreased WAT specific gene expression compared to the WT mice.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Thus, EBF2 has been identified as a potential therapeutic molecule to induce beiging.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Chromatin immunoprecipitation with sequencing (ChIP-seq) is a method used to identify protein binding sites on DNA and assess histone modifications.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] This tool has enabled examination of epigenetic regulation of browning and helps elucidate the mechanisms by which protein-DNA interactions stimulate the differentiation of beige adipocytes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Studies observing the chromatin landscapes of beige adipocytes have found that adipogenesis of these cells results from the formation of cell specific chromatin landscapes, which regulate the transcriptional program and, ultimately, control differentiation.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Using ChIP-seq in conjunction with other tools, recent studies have identified over 30 transcriptional and epigenetic factors that influence beige adipocyte development.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The thrifty gene hypothesis (also called the famine hypothesis) states that in some populations the body would be more efficient at retaining fat in times of plenty, thereby endowing greater resistance to starvation in times of food scarcity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In 1995, Jeffrey Friedman, in his residency at the Rockefeller University, together with Rudolph Leibel, Douglas Coleman et al. discovered the protein leptin that the genetically obese mouse lacked.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Leptin is produced in the white adipose tissue and signals to the hypothalamus.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] When leptin levels drop, the body interprets this as a loss of energy, and hunger increases.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Mice lacking this protein eat until they are four times their normal size.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Leptin, however, plays a different role in diet-induced obesity in rodents and humans.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Because adipocytes produce leptin, leptin levels are elevated in the obese.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] However, hunger remains, and—when leptin levels drop due to weight loss—hunger increases.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The drop of leptin is better viewed as a starvation signal than the rise of leptin as a satiety signal.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] However, elevated leptin in obesity is known as leptin resistance.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The changes that occur in the hypothalamus to result in leptin resistance in obesity are currently the focus of obesity research.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Gene defects in the leptin gene (*ob*) are rare in human obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Others have been identified as genetically partially deficient in leptin, and, in these individuals, leptin levels on the low end of the normal range can predict obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Several mutations of genes involving the melanocortins (used in brain signaling associated with appetite) and their receptors have also been identified as causing obesity in a larger portion of the population than leptin mutations.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Different cell types within adipose tissue exhibit distinct DNA methylation patterns.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Mature adipocytes and adipose progenitor cells (ASPCs) show a high degree of hypomethylation, affecting more than 50% of their regulatory regions.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] This hypomethylation is associated with the activation of genes involved in triglyceride synthesis, such as glycerol‑3‑phosphate acyltransferase 1 (GPAM).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In contrast, myeloid cells display approximately 73% hypermethylated regions, reflecting an epigenetic program opposite to that of the adipocytic lineage.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Overall, there is a direct relationship between DNA demethylation and gene expression, whereby highly expressed genes tend to exhibit low methylation levels.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] These epigenetic patterns contribute to defining the functional identity of the different cell types within subcutaneous adipose tissue (SAT).
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue has a density of ~0.9 g/ml.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Thus, a person with more adipose tissue will float more easily than a person of the same weight with more muscular tissue, since muscular tissue has a density of 1.06 g/ml.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In addition to the visible changes in adipose tissue associated with obesity, recent research indicates that the risk of developing abdominal obesity and cardiometabolic alterations also depends on the 3D organization of the genome in subcutaneous adipose tissue.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Single‑cell epigenomic studies have shown that many genetic variants associated with abdominal fat distribution (measured as WHRadjBMI) are preferentially located in active genomic regions of adipocytes.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] These regions display low levels of DNA methylation and belong to the so‑called A compartment, which is characterized by higher gene activity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] These findings suggest that adipocytes in subcutaneous adipose tissue play a key role in mediating the genetic risk associated with abdominal obesity.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] A **body fat meter** is a tool used to measure the body fat to weight ratio in the human body.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Different meters use various methods to determine the ratio.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] They tend to under-read body fat percentage.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] In contrast with clinical tools like DXA and underwater weighing, one relatively inexpensive type of body fat meter uses the principle of bioelectrical impedance analysis (BIA) in order to determine an individual's body fat percentage.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] To achieve this, the meter passes a small, harmless, electric current through the body and measures the resistance, then uses information on the person's weight, height, age, and sex to calculate an approximate value for the person's body fat percentage.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The calculation measures the total volume of water in the body (lean tissue and muscle contain a higher percentage of water than fat), and estimates the percentage of fat based on this information.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] The result can fluctuate several percentage points depending on what has been eaten and how much water has been drunk before the analysis.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] This method is quick and readily accessible, but imprecise.
[src:adipose-tissue/adipose-tissue] Alternative methods are: skin fold methods using calipers, underwater weighing, whole body air displacement plethysmography (ADP) and DXA.
